import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import BinderHoles from "../components/BinderHoles.astro";
import Backlink from "../components/Backlink.astro";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Performance Evaluation" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        During your time with Lumon, you stand to climb a most sacred ladder of
        departmental standing, responsibility, and trust.
      </p>
      <p>
        In <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>, the rungs of that
        ladder are called <strong>Kier Points</strong>, and this chapter shares
        the secrets to earning them.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2>Earning Kier Points</h2>
    <p>
      There is no fixed schedule for the awarding of Kier Points. Your
      <strong>GM</strong>
      grants them at moments of genuine significance, when an employee&#x27;s conduct
      has meaningfully served the interests of Lumon Industries.
    </p>
    <p>
      Earning a Point is a <em>story beat</em>, not a bookkeeping chore — your
      GM is encouraged to make the moment land. A few examples of conduct worthy
      of a Kier Point:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Meeting one&#x27;s quota for a full quarter without a single misstep.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Volunteering for an unpleasant task that no other employee would
          accept.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Quietly settling a dispute between coworkers before it reached the
          ears of management.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          A display of loyalty so exemplary that the Floor Manager pulls the
          employee aside to thank them personally.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2>Where the Point Goes</h2>
    <p>
      Every Kier Point is placed into a <strong>specific row</strong> of the <strong
        >Temper Analysis Chart</strong
      >
      on the LIEP — the row whose <strong>Temper</strong> drove the qualifying action.
    </p>
    <p>
      An employee who won a tense meeting through sharp <strong>WIT</strong> (parent
      Temper: <strong>DREAD</strong>) earns their Point in the
      <strong>DREAD</strong> row. An employee who soothed a hard moment with practiced
      <strong>CHEER</strong> (parent Temper:
      <strong>FROLIC</strong>) earns theirs in the
      <strong>FROLIC</strong> row. When more than one Temper might apply, your GM&#x27;s
      call is final.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="info">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u>Why row placement matters</u></strong></p>
        <p>
          Points placed in a row are added to that row&#x27;s Core Principle
          Rolls — see
          <strong>The Roll</strong> in <a href="/procedural-guidelines"
            >Procedural Guidelines</a
          >. Row placement turns your roleplay choices into mechanical
          specialization: the shape of an employee&#x27;s career becomes the
          shape of their character sheet.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2>Determining Tier</h2>
    <p>
      An employee&#x27;s current <strong>Tier</strong> is the <em>total</em>
      number of Kier Points they hold, summed across all four Temper rows.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>1 – 2 Points</strong> — Tier I</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>3 – 4 Points</strong> — Tier II</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>5 – 6 Points</strong> — Tier III
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>7 – 8 Points</strong> — Tier IV</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>9 – 10 Points</strong> — Tier V</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Each Tier carries a set of <strong>Boons</strong>
      — narrative permissions and mechanical privileges that persist for as long as
      you hold the Points that earned them. Drop a Tier, and its Boons drop with you.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>The Kier Track</h2>
    <p><em>The Corporate Path.</em></p>
    <p>
      Lumon recognizes those who exemplify our values, and the Kier Track is
      that recognition made visible. Climb it, and the company opens its doors
      to you.
    </p>
    <h3>Tier I — Associate</h3>
    <p>A standard employee in good standing.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Basic departmental access.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Eligible for standard employee benefits.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier II — Senior Associate</h3>
    <p>A proven and dependable employee.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to personnel records.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Trusted with sensitive departmental information.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier III — Distinguished Associate</h3>
    <p>An employee recognized for exceptional performance.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to restricted departmental resources.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>May request special corporate accommodations.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier IV — Chief Associate</h3>
    <p>The highest-ranking associate within the department.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Restrictions</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Only one employee may hold this title at a time. Should two
            employees qualify, the GM may stage an internal competition, or
            arbitrate the placement narratively.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to department-wide records.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>May sponsor privileges for other employees.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Considered the primary employee representative of the department.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier V — Department Chief</h3>
    <p>The official leader of the department.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Restrictions</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Only one employee may hold this title at a time.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Full departmental access.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Access to executive communications.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Authority to authorize departmental initiatives.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Direct communication with management.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h4>Kier Philosophy</h4>
    <p>
      Kier advancement grants <strong>official power</strong>
      — recognition, trust, access, responsibility, and authority. The Kier Track
      rewards those who excel within the system.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Losing Kier Points</h2>
    <p>
      Kier Points may be lost as readily as they are earned. An employee found
      to have acted against the company&#x27;s interests — a prohibited item
      discovered at their station, a confidence betrayed, a record found altered
      — may forfeit Points at the GM&#x27;s discretion.
    </p>
    <p>
      The GM decides how many Points are lost, and from which row, according to
      what occurred and how plainly it was seen. Should the loss drop an
      employee below a Tier threshold, the Tier falls with them, and its Boons
      are revoked.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Demerits and Termination</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Demerits</strong>
      are tracked separately from Kier Points. They accumulate toward
      <strong>Termination</strong> (see <strong>Burnout</strong> in <a
        href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a
      >).
    </p>
    <p>
      A Demerit is most often issued as a consequence of Burnout. The GM may
      also issue one at any time should an employee do something Lumon judges
      unforgivable, even absent Burnout.
    </p>
    <p>
      Three Demerits remains the threshold for Termination. A loss of Kier
      Points may accompany a Demerit, but does not replace one.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>On Advancement and &quot;Winning&quot;</h2>
    <p>
      Reaching Department Chief is not &quot;winning.&quot; <a
        href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a
      >
      has no win condition and no finish line. The Tiers exist to
      <em>equip</em>
      your employee; the story your GM builds, and the choices you make within it,
      are the game itself. Advancement is a tool, never a trophy.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>The Ricken Track</h2>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>Dear reader,</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >Lumon has shown you their ladder. Climb it, and they will trust
            you, promote you, and love you — right up until the day you climb
            high enough to see what you have been serving.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >There is another ladder. Lumon would pull this guide from every
            shelf for printing it, so I have printed it myself, by hand, in the
            copies I could reach. I call it the
          </em><em><strong>Ricken Track</strong></em><em
            >, after the one book on this floor worth reading.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >The machinery is the same as theirs: you earn a Point in a moment
            that matters, you place it in the row of the Temper that drove the
            act, and you sum your Points for your Tier. Lumon already drilled
            you on all that. What changes is everything it is
          </em><em><u>for</u></em><em
            >. Where Kier rewards obedience with badges, Ricken rewards
            curiosity with knowledge and contraband.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >One warning before you read on. Lumon does not love its critics.
            This Track is more dangerous than theirs — and walking both at once
            grows more dangerous the further you have come on each.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <em
        >The Resistance Path. (Yes, this whole section is mine. Read it before
        someone takes this copy from you.)</em
      >
    </p>
    <h3>Tier I — Reader</h3>
    <p>You&#x27;ve found something you weren&#x27;t meant to read.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Learn a secret rumor from the GM.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Gain access to a hidden stash location.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Persistent Contraband</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>A hidden note, page, or document.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier II — Correspondent</h3>
    <p>You&#x27;ve established contact beyond your department.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to interdepartmental information.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Ability to receive hidden messages.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Persistent Contraband</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Unauthorized keycard, or a hidden communication channel.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier III — Conspirator</h3>
    <p>You&#x27;ve become part of an underground network.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to restricted employee information.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>May call upon underground contacts for assistance.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Persistent Contraband</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Unauthorized department maps, or a record of hidden routes.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier IV — Agitator</h3>
    <p>Your actions actively influence the resistance.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Access to multiple underground contacts.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Ability to establish safe locations.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Ability to conceal evidence from management.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Once per <strong>workday</strong>, temporarily suppress the effects
            of a
            <strong>Problem</strong>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Persistent Contraband</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            A secret contact list, or the address of a hidden meeting location.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>Tier V — Awakener</h3>
    <p>You possess knowledge capable of threatening Lumon itself.</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u>Boons</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Ability to establish underground cells.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Ability to reveal hidden truths to other employees.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Once per <strong>workday</strong>, gain
            <strong>Confidence</strong>
            on any action involving Lumon secrets.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u>Persistent Contraband</u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Forbidden archives, or a high-security stolen resource.</p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h4>Ricken Philosophy</h4>
    <p>
      Ricken advancement grants <strong>unofficial power</strong>
      — secrets, connections, leverage, and knowledge. The Ricken Track rewards those
      who look beyond the system.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Contraband</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      Contraband is the currency of the resistance — the physical and
      informational scraps Lumon never meant you to hold. It comes in two forms.
    </p>
    <h3>Persistent Contraband</h3>
    <p>
      Persistent Contraband is granted by the Ricken Track at each new Tier. As
      long as the employee holds the Tier, they hold the Contraband.
    </p>
    <p>
      When a Roll would be meaningfully aided by a relevant piece of Persistent
      Contraband, the GM may choose one of:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Waive the Roll entirely</strong>
          — the action just succeeds. (You have the keycard. The door opens.)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Reduce the Roll&#x27;s Task Severity by one tier</strong>
          — Arduous becomes Demanding, Demanding becomes Routine, and so on.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Grant Confidence</strong>
          on the Roll.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If an employee drops a Tier, the GM decides which piece of Persistent
      Contraband is lost — and how. A keycard demagnetizes. A map is discovered
      by Security. A contact stops returning calls. The world finds a way.
    </p>
    <h3>Consumable Contraband</h3>
    <p>
      Consumable Contraband exists in the world independent of any Track. Any
      employee may find Consumable Contraband — by stumbling across it, by being
      given it, or by deliberately seeking it out. The GM controls availability.
    </p>
    <p>
      A Consumable item is <strong>spent</strong>
      for a guaranteed
      <strong>Success</strong>
      on a single related Roll, or to bypass a single specific obstacle. Examples
      include a smuggled note containing a one-time-use password recovery key, a smuggled
      snack that restores one stress, or a frail keycard that looks like it's about
      to snap.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>Hold it close.</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >Persistent or Consumable, any Contraband Lumon finds on you is
            taken — and the GM may hand down a
          </em><em><strong>Demerit</strong></em><em>, a loss of </em><em
            ><strong>Kier Points</strong></em
          ><em
            >, or both, depending on how plainly you were caught holding it.
            Carry it carefully. Carry it rarely.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— C.C.</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2>Losing Ricken Points</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      Points can be lost as well as earned — on my Track as much as theirs. You
      lose Ricken Points when those who trust you come to see you as too cosy
      with Lumon: accepting a promotion in plain view, naming a coworker to
      management, reporting a rumor you should have buried. Trust is the only
      currency the resistance has, and it can be spent away.
    </p>
    <p>
      The GM decides how many you lose, and from which row, by what you did and
      who saw it. Fall below a Tier, and the Tier falls with you — its Boons and
      its Persistent Contraband gone.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <hr />
    <h2>Two Paths, Shared Destinations</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      My Track and theirs mirror one another. At equal Tiers, they often reach
      the same destinations — just through different doors.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Official Keycard</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Stolen Keycard</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Department Records</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Secret Records</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Promotion</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Conspiracy</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Authority</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Leverage</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Resources</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Secrets</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong>Trust</strong>
            &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            <strong>Knowledge</strong>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      A Tier V Kier employee and a Tier V Ricken employee may ultimately stand
      in the same room. The Kier employee walks through the front door, because
      they are
      <em>authorized</em>. The Ricken employee finds a way in, because they
      <em>discovered a route nobody else knows exists</em>.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Walking Both Ladders</h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      Nothing stops you from climbing both ladders at once. Some of the bravest
      people I have known did exactly that. But understand the cost: the further
      you climb on one, the harder the other fights you. A trusted manager is
      watched for betrayal. A known troublemaker is never offered the promotion.
    </p>
    <p>
      When you reach for Points on one Track while the other is already well
      climbed, expect the GM to make you work for it:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          A higher <strong>Task Severity</strong>
          on any Roll involved.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>A Roll demanded where one would normally be waived.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Fresh <strong>opportunities for discovery</strong>
          — Lumon&#x27;s eyes notice contradictions, and the resistance notices fence-sitters.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            >That is my ladder. Walk it carefully, and trust slowly. If you want
            to know how Lumon hunts the people who walk it, the GM keeps a set
            of pages they call
          </em><a href="/classified"><em>Classified</em></a><em>
            — that is where I have hidden the most.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
